  "prompt": "After demonetization of Rs.500 and Rs.1000 notes, what will happen to old notes?",
  "response": "After the demonetization of Rs. 500 and Rs. 1000 notes in India, the old notes ceased to be legal tender. Here are the key points regarding what happened to those old notes:\n\n1. **Withdrawal from Circulation**: The old Rs. 500 and Rs. 1000 currency notes were withdrawn from circulation, which meant they could no longer be used for transactions.\n\n2. **Exchange Period**: The Reserve Bank of India (RBI) allowed individuals to exchange old notes for new ones at banks or post offices over a specified period, typically within a few months of the announcement. There were specific limits on how much could be exchanged at a time.\n\n3. **Deposits in Banks**: People could also deposit old notes into their bank accounts within the specified time frame without facing penalties.\n\n4. **After the Deadline**: After the exchange period ended, the old notes could no longer be exchanged for new currency notes or deposited in banks. However, the RBI suggested that individuals could still approach the central bank for redemption under specific conditions.\n\n5. **Legal Implications**: Holding old notes after the demonetization period was not illegal per se, but they were not usable for transactions or services.\n\n6. **Destruction of Notes**: The demonetized currency notes were subsequently destroyed by the RBI as they were no longer considered valid currency.\n\nThe demonetization aimed to combat black money, counterfeiting, and promote digital transactions in the economy.",
